			<div class="blog-post-meta">
				<p class="meta-info">Published April 5, 2026 · By the Sula Catering Team</p>
			</div>

			<p>Some Indian dishes are showstoppers at home but fall apart in a buffet tray. Others travel beautifully and somehow taste even better an hour after they leave the kitchen. After fifteen years catering <a href="/corporate">Vancouver offices</a>, we know which dishes belong on every corporate menu — and which we leave for sit-down dinners.</p>

			<h2>The Foundation: <em>Butter Chicken</em></h2>
			<p>Butter chicken is the dish that converts skeptics. It's mild enough for first-time Indian-food eaters, rich enough for connoisseurs, and travels exceptionally well — the tomato-cream sauce stays glossy and the chicken stays tender even after sitting in a chafing dish. Order halal-certified butter chicken if your team includes Muslim guests (read more about <a href="/blog/halal-indian-catering-vancouver">halal chicken</a> sourcing).</p>

			<h2>The Vegetarian Anchor: <em>Paneer Butter Masala</em></h2>
			<p>For vegetarian colleagues, paneer butter masala is the equivalent of butter chicken — same creamy tomato base, with cubes of fresh paneer instead of meat. Pair these two dishes side by side and you've covered 80% of your team without anyone feeling like they got the "second" option.</p>

			<h2>The Crowd-Pleaser: <em>Dal Makhani</em></h2>
			<p>Slow-cooked black lentils in cream and butter. Dal makhani is rich, satisfying, and naturally vegetarian and gluten-free. It also reheats well, which matters for any office lunch where the food sits for an hour before everyone gets to it.</p>

			<h2>The Showpiece: <em>Biryani</em></h2>
			<p>A proper Hyderabadi-style chicken or vegetable biryani is the dish that elevates a simple office lunch into something memorable. Layered basmati rice with caramelised onions, whole spices, and tender meat or vegetables. We serve it with raita on the side and a small portion of mirchi ka salan for guests who want extra heat.</p>

			<h2>The Greens: <em>Saag Paneer</em></h2>
			<p>For variety, add saag paneer — slow-cooked spinach with paneer cubes. It adds colour, balances the heavier curries, and gives vegetarian diners a second main option.</p>

			<h2>The Starters: <em>Samosas and Chaat</em></h2>
			<p>Mini vegetable samosas are the universally loved appetizer. They travel well, hold their shape in a chafing dish, and pair with two or three chutneys (mint, tamarind, mango) for variety. For larger events, a live chaat station with dahi puri and pani puri creates real energy — and gives guests something to talk about.</p>

			<h2>The Sides: <em>Naan, Rice, Pickles</em></h2>
			<ul>
				<li>Garlic naan — the universal favourite</li>
				<li>Vegetable pulao or jeera rice as a lighter alternative to biryani</li>
				<li>Cucumber raita for cooling spice</li>
				<li>Mango pickle and lime pickle on the side for variety</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>The Dessert: <em>Keep It Simple</em></h2>
			<p>For corporate lunches, complicated desserts are usually a mistake. We recommend gulab jamun (warm syrupy doughnut balls) or kheer (rice pudding with cardamom and pistachio). Both travel well, both are crowd-friendly, both feel celebratory without being heavy.</p>

			<h2>What to <em>Avoid</em> for Corporate Catering</h2>
			<p>Some dishes are spectacular but don't travel well. We typically don't recommend:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Dosas (best made fresh — only do these as a live station)</li>
				<li>Tandoori roti (gets dry quickly)</li>
				<li>Anything deep-fried that's been sitting (loses its texture)</li>
				<li>Highly perishable raw seafood preparations</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Add the Café <em>Touch</em></h2>
			<p>For all-day events, conferences, or client lunches that run long, add a <a href="/cafe-catering">live chai station</a> from Sula Café. Hot masala chai brewed fresh in copper urns is a small detail that turns an ordinary office lunch into something memorable.</p>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
			<p>The best corporate menu isn't the most ambitious — it's the most reliable. <a href="https://sulaindianrestaurant.com/request-a-quote/">Request a quote</a> and our coordinator will help you build the right menu for your team.</p>

